columns.text:
We can notice two things:

1. Since APR is considered 'quoted value' in this case, and EAR requires quoted value/period, we can use APR/period in the formula OR we can calculate the periodic rate and use that instead;

2. EAR $\ne$ APR as EAR compounds, while APR flatly multiplies EXCEPT if there is no compounding and rate is predefined as annual\yearly, then EAR = APR.
